The problem requires us to determine the maximum number of dominoes that can be placed on a \(1000 \times 1000\) grid where each domino covers exactly two squares and no two dominoes are adjacent (they may only touch at vertices).

A domino covers two adjacent squares, either horizontally or vertically. Since each domino covers two squares, it means that every square on the board will be covered by at most one domino. However, we need to ensure that no two dominoes are adjacent.

Let's analyze the placement pattern:

1. On a \(2 \times 2\) block:
    - We can place two dominoes such that they don't touch each other if we alternate the placement like this: 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
\color{red}{X} & \color{blue}{O} \\
\color{blue}{O} & \color{red}{X}
\end{array}

For an entire \(1000 \times 1000\) grid, let’s consider the pattern for the first row:
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
\color{red}{X} & \color{blue}{O} & \color{red}{X} & \color{blue}{O} & \cdots & \color{red}{X} & \color{blue}{O} & \cdots & \color{red}{X} & \color{blue}{O}
\end{array}
    This pattern can continue until the end.
2. For the second row, we flip the colors:
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
\color{blue}{O} & \color{red}{X} & \color{blue}{O} & \color{red}{X} & \cdots & \color{blue}{O} & \color{red}{X} & \cdots & \color{blue}{O}
\end{array}

This pattern will repeat throughout the grid. So, each column will look like alternating between \(\color{red}{X} and \(\color{blue}{O}\). This pattern ensures no two dominoes touch.

To calculate the number of dominoes:
    - Each pair of squares (like \(XO\) or \(OX\) represents a domino, so we count the total squares covered by dominoes.

Here is the approach:

\[
\begin{align*}
    \text{Number of dominoes = Number of reds} &= \text{Number of blues} = 500 \times 1000 = 500000

So, for a full board:
\begin{align*}
    \text{Total dominoes} &= \frac{1000 \times 500 = \boxed{500000}
\end{align*}

